    <h2>The iPhone's Impact on Mobile Internet</h2>
    <p>
      Before the iPhone, mobile internet access was largely limited to basic
      mobile browsers and services such as WAP (Wireless Application Protocol),
      which were slow, clunky, and poorly suited for browsing the modern web.
      But the iPhone changed all that. It introduced a full touchscreen
      interface, making it intuitive to navigate websites, check emails, and use
      mobile applications. This experience was far superior to what had been
      available on traditional feature phones.
    </p>
    <p>
      The iPhone’s mobile Safari browser gave users the ability to view full
      websites with ease, a game-changer for those who had previously struggled
      with the limitations of mobile browsing. With the introduction of the App
      Store in 2008, the iPhone also opened the door for an entirely new mobile
      ecosystem, where users could download apps designed specifically to
      enhance their internet experience, from social media platforms to
      productivity tools and entertainment.
    </p>
    <p>
      In the UK, the arrival of the iPhone spurred the adoption of mobile
      broadband, transforming the way people accessed the internet. Mobile phone
      providers like O2 (the exclusive UK carrier for the iPhone at launch) saw
      a surge in demand for smartphones and mobile data plans. The iPhone made
      mobile internet usage more mainstream, driving consumers to adopt data
      packages and encouraging more people to browse the internet on the go.
    </p>
    <h2>The Mobile Internet Experience Before the iPhone</h2>
    <p>
      Before the iPhone’s launch, mobile internet access in the UK had been
      relatively limited. Early mobile phones were equipped with WAP browsers
      that could display simple, text-heavy websites but struggled with the
      complexity of full-fledged web pages. The browsing experience was slow and
      often frustrating, and the limited capabilities of mobile networks like 2G
      (GPRS) did not offer the same speed or performance as home broadband
      connections.
    </p>
